CHAPTER 1: HOW WE GOT HERE
You ever make a decision that you know is gonna ruin your life, but you do it anyway?
Yeah. Me too.
My name is Cole Brennan. I'm sitting in my car in an underground parking garage at 2 AM, chain-smoking Marlboros and staring at blueprints that are probably going to get me killed. I'm thirty-eight years old. I used to be a financial crimes specialist—one of the good guys, believe it or not. Now? Now I launder money for a man who makes people disappear for a living.
I've been doing it for six years.
Six years of washing blood money through fake consulting firms. Six years of looking over my shoulder every time I leave the house. Six years of lying to my wife—ex-wife now—about why Daddy's always "working late." Six years of watching my daughter grow up thinking her father is just another suit who cares more about spreadsheets than soccer games.
I light another cigarette with the ember of the first one. The ashtray is overflowing. The car smells like smoke and stale coffee and desperation. Smokers don't drink—that's my rule. My only rule, apparently, because I've broken every other one that ever mattered.
And tonight? Tonight I'm about to do something monumentally stupid.
I'm going to rob Vincent Harlan. The Broker. The man who owns me. The man who owns half of Los Angeles.
You're probably thinking, Cole, that's suicide.
You'd be right.
But here's the thing about being dead inside for six years—you stop caring about staying alive. When you've spent that long as a puppet with someone else pulling the strings, when you've looked your daughter in the eye and lied so many times you can't remember what the truth feels like anymore, when your wife packs up and leaves because she can't watch you destroy yourself any longer—well, at that point, what the fuck do you have to lose?
I look at the blueprints spread across my passenger seat. Real estate holdings. Security rotations. Financial records. Shell companies within shell companies within shell companies. Everything I've compiled over the last three weeks since I walked into Vincent's restaurant and told him the one word he's never heard before.
No.

Three weeks earlier.
The restaurant was called Cicada. One of those places where the rich go to pretend they're not criminals. White tablecloths. Overpriced wine. Waiters who'd seen too much and said too little. Vincent liked it because it had a private room in the back where he conducted his "business meetings." I'd been to a dozen of them over the years. Always the same routine. Vincent would order for the table, make small talk, then slide a folder across with the details of whatever he needed me to launder that month.
I walked in at noon. Bright daylight. That should've been my first warning—Vincent usually preferred evening meetings. Darkness suited him better.
He was sitting with two lawyers I'd seen before and a bodyguard by the door I hadn't. Vincent himself was fifty-four, average height, average build, forgettable face—the kind of man you'd pass on the street and never remember. That was his genius. He dressed well but not flashy. Grey suit. No logos. No jewelry. He could've been a consultant, a banker, an insurance adjuster. Anyone. No one.
He looked up when I entered and smiled. The kind of smile that never reaches the eyes.
"Cole. Sit. Have you eaten? The salmon here is excellent."
I sat across from him. Didn't pick up the menu. My stomach had been twisted in knots for two days, ever since I'd opened the preliminary files he'd sent and realized what this job actually was.
"I'm not doing the job."
The words came out flat. Final. I'd practiced them in the mirror that morning while Sarah was getting the kids ready for school, trying to sound confident. Trying to sound like a man who wasn't about to piss off the most dangerous person in Los Angeles.
Vincent's smile faded like someone had flipped a switch.
"I'm sorry," he said slowly, setting down his fork with deliberate care. "I must have misheard you."
"You heard me fine."
One of the lawyers shifted in his seat. The bodyguard's hand moved to his side. Vincent held up a finger—barely a movement—and everyone froze.
Silence. Vincent dabbed his mouth with a napkin, taking his time. The clock on the wall ticked. Someone laughed in the main dining room. The sound felt like it was coming from another world.
"We had an agreement," Vincent said, and his voice had gone cold now. All pretense of friendliness evaporated. "Six years ago. You work for me, your family stays safe. That was the deal."
"The deal was I launder money," I said, fighting to keep my voice steady. "Clean money. Business money. Real estate, consulting fees, legitimate-looking transactions. Not this."
I slid the folder across the table. Inside were the details of what he wanted me to do—launder twenty million dollars for a cartel operation that would flood three neighborhoods with enough fentanyl to kill hundreds. Maybe thousands. The money would flow through a pharmaceutical distribution company, through a medical supply chain, through a network so clean it would look like a charitable operation. And by the time anyone traced it back, the bodies would already be in the ground.
Vincent didn't even look at the folder.
"You have a problem with the nature of the transaction?"
"I have a problem with funding a massacre. Yeah."
He leaned back in his chair, studying me like I was a bug under glass. Something to be examined. Classified. Dealt with.
"Cole. Do you know how many people depend on me? Cops. Politicians. Businessmen. This entire city runs because I make the hard decisions that people like you are too weak to make. I provide stability. I provide order. What do you provide? Moral objections?"
"I'm not doing it," I repeated.
Something shifted in Vincent's expression. The mask slipped, just for a second, and I saw something cold and reptilian underneath. Something that had probably always been there, waiting.
"Then your family is done." His voice didn't rise. Didn't need to. "Your daughter—Emma, is it? Seventeen now. Beautiful girl. Smart. Takes after her father, I hear. Berkeley-bound, right? Would be a shame if something happened before she got that acceptance letter. Or your son. Ryan. Seven years old. Still believes in superheroes, I bet. Still thinks his daddy's one of them."
The room tilted. My hands clenched into fists under the table.
"You touch them—"
"I won't touch them," Vincent interrupted, voice smooth as silk. "I'll never touch them. I'll just make a phone call. And someone else will. Someone you'll never find. Someone who'll make it look like an accident. A robbery gone wrong. A drunk driver. These things happen in Los Angeles, Cole. Every single day."
I stood up so fast my chair scraped across the floor with a screech that made everyone in the restaurant look over. The lawyers tensed. The bodyguard's hand went to his jacket. But Vincent just sat there, perfectly calm, that cold smile back on his face.
"You touch them," I said, and my voice was shaking now, rage and fear mixing into something toxic, "and I'll burn everything you've built to the fucking ground."
Vincent laughed. Actually laughed. A soft, amused sound like I'd told him a clever joke.
"With what? You're a washed-up accountant playing criminal. I own this city. I own the cops. I own the judges. I own the politicians. I own YOU. Sit down before you embarrass yourself further."
I didn't sit.
"Watch me."
I turned and walked out. Through the main dining room where well-dressed people ate expensive food and pretended not to notice the scene we'd just made. Through the entrance where the valet looked at me with wide eyes. Out into the bright LA sunshine that felt like a spotlight.
My hands were shaking so badly I could barely get my keys out.

Back in the car now, three weeks later, I can still see his face. That smug fucking smile. The certainty in his eyes that I was nothing. Nobody. A problem he could erase with one phone call.
You know what he did next?
He sent people to my house. Not immediately—Vincent's too smart for that. He waited three days. Long enough for me to think maybe I'd gotten away with it. Long enough for me to start breathing again.
Then a black SUV started parking across from Emma's school. Same SUV, same spot, every afternoon pickup. Never did anything. Just sat there. Watching.
Sarah noticed first. Called me at work, voice tight with controlled panic.
"Cole. There's a car. It's been following me."
"You're sure?"
"I'm fucking sure, Cole. What did you do? What did you get us into?"
I couldn't tell her. Didn't know how to explain six years of lies.
The next day, one of Vincent's people walked past Ryan at the park. Didn't touch him. Didn't say anything. Just walked past, close enough that Ryan felt it, looked up at me with those big seven-year-old eyes and asked, "Daddy, why did that man smile at me?"
That night, Sarah packed.
I came home from another sleepless day of trying to figure out how to fix this, how to protect them, and found suitcases in the hallway. Emma's duffel bag. Ryan's backpack with his drawings sticking out the top.
Sarah was in the kitchen, methodically loading dishes into a box even though we both knew she wasn't taking them.
"Sarah—"
"Don't." She didn't look at me. "Just don't, Cole."
"Let me explain—"
"You've been explaining for six years. And every explanation is a lie." She finally turned, and her eyes were red but dry. She'd cried herself out already. "I don't know what you've gotten us into. But I'm not staying to watch you destroy them."
"Where will you go?"
"Somewhere you can't find us. Somewhere THEY can't find us." She picked up the box, balanced it on her hip. "When this is over—if you survive whatever the hell you're doing—don't come looking for us. Not until you can promise me they're safe. Really safe. Forever."
She walked past me. Emma was waiting in the hallway with Ryan's hand in hers. My daughter. Seventeen years old. Already looked like her mother. Same sharp eyes. Same ability to see through bullshit.
She stopped in front of me. Ryan didn't—he just buried his face in Emma's side, not understanding why they were leaving, why Daddy looked so scared.
"Whatever you're doing," Emma said quietly, "don't die, okay?"
My throat closed up. Couldn't speak.
Her jaw tightened. She had her mother's strength too.
"I love you," she said. "Even though you're a fucking liar."
First time she'd ever cursed at me. Broke my heart clean in half.
Then they were gone. Door closing. Car starting. Red taillights disappearing down the street.
I stood in the empty house and realized: Vincent had already taken everything. My family. My life. My future. All that was left was the choice of how I died.
Running? That was dying slowly, looking over my shoulder forever, knowing he'd find them eventually.
Or I could fight back.

I light another cigarette and stare at the blueprints. Vincent's real estate empire. His shell companies. His network of cops and politicians and criminals. Everything I've spent six years helping him build. Everything I now know how to tear down.
That's when I realized—I had two choices. Run and spend the rest of my life looking over my shoulder, waiting for Vincent to make good on his threats. Or find the craziest sons of bitches in Los Angeles and take the fight to him.
I get out of the car and walk across the empty parking garage toward the dive bar I can see in the distance. My footsteps echo.
First stop: my old friend Ray Carson. Ex-cop. Ex-husband. Ex-everything. We worked together once, years ago, before everything went to shit for both of us. Before I took the plea deal and he went undercover and we both ended up as ghosts of who we used to be.
If anyone was broken enough to say yes to this insanity, it was Ray.
I push open the bar door. Smoke and stale beer hit me immediately. There he is—end of the bar, halfway through a bottle of whiskey, looking exactly as destroyed as I expected.
Ray Carson. The first piece of my suicide mission.
I walk over and sit down two stools away.
"Ray Carson. Thought you'd be dead by now."
He doesn't look up. Just raises his glass slightly.
"Working on it."
Yeah. This is going to work out great.
